What warnings does splint generate on your Part 3 code, and what are
your disagreements with them? Copy the splint warnings here, and
express your disagreement after each warning. If there are no
warnings, then write "None."

(1) Many warnings of the form:
   "Return value type enum { SUCCESS, ... } does not match declared type int"
   "Operands of != have incompatible types (int, enum { SUCCESS, ... })"
We disagree. These arise because a4def.h defines status codes as an
anonymous enum, but our functions return int per the ft.h interface.
In C, enum values are implicitly convertible to int. This pattern is
inherited from the provided DT code infrastructure.

(2) Many warnings of the form:
   "Operand of ! is non-boolean (boolean): !bIsInitialized"
   "Test expression for if not boolean, type boolean"
We disagree. These arise because a4def.h defines boolean as an enum
type, and splint does not recognize it as a boolean without the
-booltype flag. The usage is correct.

(3) nodeFT.c Node_find and Node_hasChild:
   "Return value type int does not match declared type boolean"
We disagree. DynArray_bsearch returns int (0 or 1), which we return
as boolean (FALSE=0, TRUE=1). The implicit conversion is correct.

(4) Many warnings of the form:
   "Null storage oPPath passed as non-null param"
   "Null storage oNNode passed as non-null param"
   "Function returns with null storage derivable from parameter"
We disagree. In each case, the code checks for NULL or error
conditions before the potentially-null pointer is used. Splint does
not track control flow precisely enough to see that the NULL case has
already been handled by an early return.

(5) Many warnings of the form:
   "Only storage ... derived from released storage is not released"
   "Implicitly temp storage ... assigned to implicitly only"
   "Fresh storage ... not released before return"
We disagree. These concern splint's ownership annotations. Our code
correctly manages memory: Node_free recursively frees children and
their paths, and returned pointers are owned by the caller per the
interface contract. These are false positives from splint's static
analysis limitations.

(6) nodeFT.c Node_new:
   "Variable ulIndex used before definition"
We disagree. ulIndex is always set by Node_hasChild or Node_find
before it is used. The path where ulIndex is used (oNParent != NULL)
always calls one of those functions first.

(7) nodeFT.c Node_new:
   "Storage psNew->pvContents is released in one path, but live"
We disagree. When Node_addChild fails, we free psNew->pvContents
in the file branch and DynArray_free in the directory branch. The
storage is correctly cleaned up on each path.

(8) nodeFT.c Node_getContents / Node_getPath / Node_getParent:
   "Function returns reference to parameter"
   "Released storage ... reachable from parameter at return point"
We disagree. These are accessor functions that intentionally return
pointers to internal data. The caller does not own or free the
returned pointer. This is standard practice for accessor functions.

(9) nodeFT.c Node_setContents:
   "Null storage returned as non-null: NULL"
We disagree. Returning NULL signals allocation failure. The caller
is expected to check for NULL. The /*@null@*/ annotation is not used
because we follow the existing DT code conventions.

(10) ft.c:
   "Function malloc expects arg 1 to be size_t gets int: 1"
   "Operands of != have incompatible types (size_t, int)"
We disagree. The integer literal 1 is safely promoted to size_t.
This is standard C behavior.

(11) nodeFT.h:
   "Function exported but not used outside nodeFT: Node_find"
   "Function exported but not used outside nodeFT: Node_addChild"
   "Function exported but not used outside nodeFT: Node_compare"
We disagree. These functions are declared in the header as part of
the module's interface. They are available for use by other modules
or for testing, even if ft.c does not currently call them directly.

(12) dynarray.h / path.h:
   "Function ... declared but not defined"
These modules are compiled separately and linked. This is not an
error in our code.

(13) ft_client.c warnings:
All splint warnings in ft_client.c originate from the provided
client code and are not part of our implementation.

